  "success": true,
  "output": "## Analysis\n\nNote: this is a Python asyncio job-scraper (fetchers → filters → SQLite store → notifiers), not a web app — there's no React frontend, so I mapped the requested categories onto Python-equivalents (sync blocking I/O instead of re-renders, SQLite round-trips instead of N+1 ORM queries).\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (highest impact)\n\n`Store.diff()` issues one `SELECT` per job, in a loop, for every fetch (Amazon/Microsoft alone can return 400+ jobs per run):\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n```\n\nFix: batch the lookup into one (chunked) query, then do all writes with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):          # stay under SQLite's 999-var limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        qmarks = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        rows = cur.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qmarks})\", chunk\n        ).fetchall()\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in rows})\n\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = job.content_hash\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev is None:\n            new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now, h)\n        elif prev != h:\n            changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now, h)\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                         [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) DB round-trips into O(N/900), and batches all the unchanged-job `last_seen` updates instead of one `UPDATE` per row. (`_insert`/`_update` should take `h` as a param instead of recomputing it — see #3.)\n\n### 2. Redundant regex recompilation — `filters.py:11-12, 21-26`\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` **on every job**, recompiling the same regex list N times for N jobs:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled per job!\n```\n\nFix — compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n(`match` then just does `any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude)` directly — no `_compile` inside.)\n\n### 3. Wasted deep-copy + double hash computation — `models.py:71-75`\n\n`Job.raw` is set on every parsed job (full ATS payload, sometimes large) but **grep confirms it is never read anywhere** except being popped immediately in `to_row()`. Worse, `to_row()` calls `dataclasses.asdict(self)`, which recursively deep-copies every field — including `raw` — only to discard it:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)      # deep-copies raw's full nested payload for nothing\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)\n    ...\n```\n\nAnd `content_hash` gets computed twice per new/changed job: once in `Store.diff` for comparison, again inside `to_row()`.\n\nFix:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self, content_hash: str | None = None) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    return {\n        \"key\": self.key, \"source\": self.source, \"company\": self.company,\n        \"external_id\": self.external_id, \"title\": self.title, \"url\": self.url,\n        \"location\": self.location, \"department\": self.department,\n        \"employment_type\": self.employment_type, \"posted_at\": self.posted_at,\n        \"salary_range\": self.salary_range,\n        \"content_hash\": content_hash if content_hash is not None else self.content_hash,\n    }\n```\n\nIf `raw` genuinely isn't needed downstream, consider dropping it after parsing (or not populating it at all) — it's pure memory overhead held for the process lifetime.\n\n### 4. Blocking, serial notifiers inside an async pipeline — `notify.py:105-109`, `pipeline.py:42-44`\n\n`dispatch()` runs 5 notifiers **sequentially**, and each does blocking I/O (`httpx.post`, `smtplib.SMTP`) directly inside `pipeline.run`, which is `async`. Each blocking call stalls the event loop and they don't overlap — Slack, webhook, email, and SMS calls all wait on each other even though they're independent.\n\nFix — run them concurrently off the event loop:\n\n```python\nasync def dispatch_async(new, changed) -> None:\n    async def _run(fn):\n        try:\n            await asyncio.to_thread(fn, new, changed)\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"  ! notifier {fn.__name__} failed: {e}\")\n    await asyncio.gather(*(_run(fn) for fn in NOTIFIERS))\n```\n\nand `await dispatch_async(new, changed)` in `pipeline.run`. For `notify_slack`/`notify_webhook`/`notify_sms`, switching to `httpx.AsyncClient` instead of `httpx.post` would avoid the thread hop entirely.\n\n### 5. Caching opportunity: no conditional requests — `fetchers.py:_get_json/_get_text`\n\nEvery run does a full re-fetch of every board (Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix run 30-40 sequential paginated requests each) with no `ETag`/`If-Modified-Since` reuse between the 12h-scheduled runs. For sources that return them (Greenhouse, Lever, etc. typically support `ETag`), threading a small on-disk cache of `(url → etag)` through `_request` and short-circuiting on `304` would cut bandwidth and latency for unchanged boards. Lower priority since these are cheap JSON APIs, but worth it for the bespoke HTML-scraping fetchers (D.E. Shaw, Two Sigma) which currently always re-download and re-regex full HTML pages.\n\n### Not an issue (checked, ruled out)\n- `fetch_all` correctly shares one pooled `httpx.AsyncClient` with a semaphore (`concurrency=8`) and closes it in `finally` — no leak.\n- Paginated fetchers (`fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, etc.) are sequential *by necessity* — they don't know the next offset is empty until they see the current page, so this isn't a fixable N+1; parallelizing would risk rate-limiting on unauthenticated public endpoints.\n\n**Priority order**: #1 (N+1 store writes) and #3 (raw-payload deep-copy) matter most since both scale with total jobs fetched (thousands per run); #2 and #4 are cheap, isolated fixes; #5 is a nice-to-have for the scheduled 12h cadence.\n",
